The best approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package rather than rolling your own wrapper. It's battle-tested and covers `File.*`, `Directory.*`, `Path.*`, etc.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool FolderExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

// File.ReadAllText
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/data/config.json"));

// File.WriteAllText
service.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

// Directory.Exists
Assert.True(service.FolderExists("/data"));
Assert.False(service.FolderExists("/nope"));
```

**Key points:**
- Only wrap what you actually call — `IFileSystem` already covers your three statics.
- Register as `AddSingleton` — `FileSystem` is stateless.
- `MockFileSystem` is an in-memory filesystem, so tests are fast and don't touch disk.

